<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="207" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="207">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. adriatica" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adriatica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">D. adriatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in the area of the Dinaric Alps. Known in Slovenia, Croatia, and Bosnia and Herzegovina (
<bibRefCitation author="Weidlich, M" journalOrPublisher="hu" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" pagination="15 - 18" refId="B44" refString="Weidlich, M, 2012. Ein Beitrag zur Verbreitung und Oekologie von Brevantennia adriatica (Rebel, 1919) (Lepidoptera: Psychidae). Microlepidoptera. hu 4: 15 - 18" title="Ein Beitrag zur Verbreitung und Oekologie von Brevantennia adriatica (Rebel, 1919) (Lepidoptera: Psychidae). Microlepidoptera." volume="4" year="2012">Weidlich 2012</bibRefCitation>
: 16, 
<bibRefCitation author="Weidlich, M" journalOrPublisher="Entomologische Nachrichten und Berichte" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" pagination="53 - 57" refId="B46" refString="Weidlich, M, 2015. Brevantennia gorskikotarica n. sp. aus Kroatien und ein weiterer Beitrag zu den Vorkommen von Brevantennia adriatica (Rebel, 1919) auf dem Balkan (Lepidoptera, Psychidae). Entomologische Nachrichten und Berichte 59 (1): 53 - 57" title="Brevantennia gorskikotarica n. sp. aus Kroatien und ein weiterer Beitrag zu den Vorkommen von Brevantennia adriatica (Rebel, 1919) auf dem Balkan (Lepidoptera, Psychidae)." volume="59" year="2015">2015</bibRefCitation>
: 65. 
<bibRefCitation author="Arnscheid, WR" editor="Karsholt, O" journalOrPublisher="Leiden and Boston (Brill) Volume" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" pagination="1 - 423" refId="B4" refString="Arnscheid, WR, Weidlich, M, 2017. Psychidae. In: Karsholt, O, Mutanen, M, Nuss, M, Eds., Microlepidoptera of Europe. Leiden and Boston (Brill) Volume 8: 1 - 423" title="Psychidae." volume="8" volumeTitle="Microlepidoptera of Europe." year="2017">Arnscheid and Weidlich 2017</bibRefCitation>
: 74).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="207">
Slovenia is the northern border of its distribution range, with presence in Brkini and surrounding hills: 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Snežnik">Sneznik</normalizedToken>
in the east, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Vremščica">Vremscica</normalizedToken>
in the north and Slavnik in the west. All Slovenian localities are ilustrated in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Distribution map of subgenus Dahlica Brevantennia species in Slovenia. 1. Prelovce, Vremscica; 2. Potok Mrzlek, Ribnica; 3. Zlebovi, Koritnice; 4. Devin, Zupnica; 5. Slavnik; 6. Mislice, Brkini; 7. Pregarje, Huje; 8. Obrov, Brkini (Weidlich 2012); 9. Gozd Martuljek; 10. Ratece, Gorenjska; 11. Mala Mojstrovka; 12. Mlinarica, Zg. Trenta; 13. Strmec na Predelu; 14. Kladje, Cerkno; 15. Zgornja Sorica; 16. Gradisce, Naklo; 17. Crnivec pod Plesivcem; 18. Strmec, Raduha; 19. Cezlak, Oplotnica; 20. Tolsti vrh, Mislinja; 21. Paski Kozjak; 22. Mrzlo Polje, Gracnica; 23. Lanise, Hrusica; 24. Nanos; 25. Kurescek, Zelimlje; 26. Mala Slevica, Velike Lasce; 27. Ravni vrh, Sodrazica; 28. Retje, Ribnica; 29. Breg pri Ribnici na Dolenjskem; 30. Trava, Podplanina; 31. Triglav, Julijske Alpe; 32. Kanin, Julijske Alpe; 33. Mangart, Julijske Alpe; 34. Stol, Karavanke; 35. Belca, Karavanke." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.45.81674.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702859" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">11</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="207" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="207">
We found this species well-represented in various biotopes with a mainly humid character. The lowest locality, where we found larval cases was a south-west facing slope of the cold valley of Potok Mrzlek (420 m), where the species inhabits sunny, mossy and lightly overgrown rocks consisting of Eocene flysch sandstone, just 10 m above the creek. Most other localities were found in south to south-west facing slopes in Illyric 
<taxonomicName genus="Ostryo" lsidName="Ostryo" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" rank="genus">Ostryo</taxonomicName>
-Quercetum zonal forest community (
<taxonomicName genus="Ostryo" lsidName="Ostryo" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Ostryo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- 
<taxonomicName genus="Carpinion" lsidName="Carpinion orientalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Carpinion orientalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) from 600-700 m elevation. The subsoil here consists of limestone. Larval cases were fixed on the south side of rocks, retaining walls and bark of trees. We noticed that the larvae are likely to avoid places with high light intensity; micro-localities shadowed with vegetation are more populated. The most typical population of this zone is 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Črni">Crni</normalizedToken>
Vrh, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Vremščica">Vremscica</normalizedToken>
(680 m) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. D. adriatica. a. Adult male resting on rock, Potok Mrzlek; b. Fresh adult female in assembling mode, Potok Mrzlek; c. Illyric Ostryo - Quercetum zonal forest community, natural habitat of D. adriatica, Crni Vrh, Vremscica, 680 m." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.45.81674.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702850" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">2c</figureCitation>
). It is interesting that the species is also represented on south-facing meadows at higher elevations, usually just above the edge of the Illyrian 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Fagus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Fagus sylvatica" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sylvatica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Fagus sylvatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forests zone (
<taxonomicName genus="Aremonio" lsidName="Aremonio" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Aremonio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- 
<taxonomicName genus="Fagion" lsidName="Fagion" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Fagion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) from 940-1010 m. Due to the higher elevation and consequently the colder climate, the larval cases were found on the warmest places: on the south side of rocks, usually where rocks were lying in larger groups - Devin, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Župnica">Zupnica</normalizedToken>
(1010 m).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="207">The species is univoltine. The adults are on the wing, depending on the location from late March to early May.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="207" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="207">
The first record of the presence of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. adriatica" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adriatica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">D. adriatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Slovenia dates back to the year 1919. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rebel, H" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen des naturwissenschaftlichen Vereins der Steiermark" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" refId="B26" refString="Rebel, H, 1919. Zur Kenntnis palaearktischer Talaeporiiden. Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift &quot;Iris&quot; 32 (3/4) [1918]: 95-112." title="Zur Kenntnis palaearktischer Talaeporiiden. Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift &quot; Iris &quot; 32 (3 / 4) [1918]: 95 - 112." year="1919">Rebel (1919</bibRefCitation>
: 110) reports one male specimen caught in Istrien (H. Kozina, leg. Naufock, 10. Mai '08). By the place name &quot;H. Kozina&quot; he probably considered the villages Hrpelje and Kozina in Slovenia, or most likely the Kozina railway station there. Travelling by train was most popular at that time. The single specimen showed slightly wider and darker wings than specimens from type locality Senj (
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Zengg”">&quot;Zengg&quot;</normalizedToken>
), Croatia, and therefore the author defines it as &quot;belongs probably also to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rebel" baseAuthorityYear="1919" class="Insecta" family="Psychidae" genus="Dahlica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dahlica adriatica" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adriatica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">Dahlica adriatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot;. This uncertainty is likely the reason why 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. adriatica" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adriatica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">D. adriatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not subsequently placed on the list of the Slovenian fauna, despite the fact that that is has been confirmed as present many times by Slovenian entomologists (Mojmir Lasan, personal communication 2012). The species was officially included in the list in 2012 (
<bibRefCitation author="Weidlich, M" journalOrPublisher="hu" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" pagination="15 - 18" refId="B44" refString="Weidlich, M, 2012. Ein Beitrag zur Verbreitung und Oekologie von Brevantennia adriatica (Rebel, 1919) (Lepidoptera: Psychidae). Microlepidoptera. hu 4: 15 - 18" title="Ein Beitrag zur Verbreitung und Oekologie von Brevantennia adriatica (Rebel, 1919) (Lepidoptera: Psychidae). Microlepidoptera." volume="4" year="2012">Weidlich 2012</bibRefCitation>
: 16).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="207">
The genital index of males slightly deviates from the known values, which were 0.61-0.64 (
<bibRefCitation author="Weidlich, M" journalOrPublisher="Entomologische Nachrichten und Berichte" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" pagination="165 - 168" refId="B43" refString="Weidlich, M, 1996. Eine neue Psychide aus Nordungarn - Brevantennia herrmanni n. sp. (Lep., Psychidae). Entomologische Nachrichten und Berichte 40 (3): 165 - 168" title="Eine neue Psychide aus Nordungarn - Brevantennia herrmanni n. sp. (Lep., Psychidae)." volume="40" year="1996">Weidlich 1996</bibRefCitation>
: 167, 
<bibRefCitation author="Weidlich, M" journalOrPublisher="hu" pageId="0" pageNumber="207" pagination="15 - 18" refId="B44" refString="Weidlich, M, 2012. Ein Beitrag zur Verbreitung und Oekologie von Brevantennia adriatica (Rebel, 1919) (Lepidoptera: Psychidae). Microlepidoptera. hu 4: 15 - 18" title="Ein Beitrag zur Verbreitung und Oekologie von Brevantennia adriatica (Rebel, 1919) (Lepidoptera: Psychidae). Microlepidoptera." volume="4" year="2012">2012</bibRefCitation>
: 15). The new index is slightly higher, from 0.61-0.68 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Graphical representation of genital indexes and classes of cloaking scales of all species in subgenus Dahlica Brevantennia (after Arnscheid and Weidlich 2017, enriched by our own investigations)." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.45.81674.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702857" pageId="0" pageNumber="207">9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
